<article>
    <h1>Ong Sor Fern</h1>
    <h2>Se&#xAD;nior Cul&#xAD;ture Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent rec&#xAD;om&#xAD;mends</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200731/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-31"><time>2020-07-31</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>KING (R18)</p>
    <p>Ac­tress Jo Tan (right) de­liv­ers a tour de force in this live-streamed per­for­mance, which is avail­able on YouTube for a lim­ited pe­riod of time. Not only does she play mul­ti­ple char­ac­ters, but she also wrote the script for this one-wo­man show.</p>
    <p>Mousy Geok Yen is a pub­lic re­la­tions ex­ec­u­tive, en­gaged to a nice insurance agent Matthew. Her safe, sta­ble life gets turned up­side down when on an im­pulse, she at­tends an of­fice party in the guise of a man, Stir­ling da Silva. She dis­cov­ers the drag scene cour­tesy of her ex­pa­tri­ate boss and drag queen Ethan, and finds a new lease of life in in­hab­it­ing the straight-talk­ing male per­sona of Stir­ling.</p>
    <p>Tan’s script, de­vel­oped un­der the dra­maturgy of Check­point The­atre and staged un­der the aus­pices of T:>Works’ N.O.W. fes­ti­val, is a multi-lay­ered marvel.</p>
    <p>Through the girl-next-door lens of Geok Yen, Tan ex­ca­vates the many lay­ers of so­cial ex­pec­ta­tions en­coded in gen­der roles. From the dorky cis­male as­sump­tions of Matthew to the trau­ma­tised angst of Ethan to the awak­en­ing cis­gen­der fem­i­nism of Geok Yen, the script deftly ad­dresses dis­crim­i­na­tion, sex­ism and chau­vin­ism with nu­ance, sen­si­tiv­ity and a large dose of hu­mour that is very of­ten laugh-out-loud funny.</p>
    <p>Most im­pres­sively, Tan switches char­ac­ters at the drop of a pair of sun­glasses, the toss of a feather boa and the change of an ac­cent. The min­i­mal props, com­bined with pre­ci­sion-timed cuts to dif­fer­ent cam­era an­gles, help cue the au­di­ence to fol­low the light­ning-fast di­a­logue ex­changes. Film-maker Jas­mine Ng proves a dab hand at help­ing to bridge the gap be­tween the­atre and video in her the­atre de­but as di­rec­tor.</p>
    <p>This thought-pro­vok­ing watch about what it means to be fe­male is a right royal treat, per­fect for the long week­end.</p>
    <p>WHERE: YouTube (str.sg/JnZ8) WHEN: Till Sun, 11.59pm AD­MIS­SION: Free</p>
    <p>INFO: str.sg/JsE7</p>

